ays that black U.S. authors have reframed fundamental questions about racial identity, personhood, and the law from the nineteenth into the twenty-first centuries. Legal Fictions is a bold declaration that the black body is thoroughly bound by law and an unflinching look at the implications of that claim.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Okt 2020) 0aAfrican AmericansxLegal status, laws, etc.xHistory. 0aAmerican literaturexAfrican American authorsxHistory and criticism. 0aRace discriminationxLaw and legislationzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aRace in literature. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDUK eBook-Package 2014-2015z978311071182040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780822377054zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780822377054423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780822377054.jpg  a978-3-11-071182-0  DUK eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_DUK_ALL  aEBA_DUK_EALL  aEBA_DUK_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles